Europe
------
[1] Russia (Smolensk ex Tula)
Date: Sun 15 Dec 2013
Source: Zdorovye [in Russian, trans., edited]
<bit.ly/1a25EnI>


The Press Service of the Smolensk Region has reported an outbreak of measles cases in the region. The diagnosis of measles was confirmed in 3 residents of the village of Valutina: 2 young men aged 24 and 26, and a 6 month old baby. The 3 cases were classified as imported cases, and it was established that the diseased had been contracted in Tula region. To prevent an outbreak of measles in the village, all local residents have been vaccinated against the disease, a total of 82 people, all of whom had contact with one or other of the 3 measles cases.

The Regional Emergencies Ministry stated that measles is often a cause of early death among young children worldwide. In adults, the disease can take a severe clinical form. Most often, measles outbreaks have occurred in the period from December to May with peaks occurring every 2 to 4 years.

Measles is an acute infectious disease, followed by fever up to 40-41 deg C [104-105.8 deg F], inflammation of mucous membranes of the nose and mouth, rash, and intoxication of the whole organism. Most complications occur in children under the age of 5 years.

