[2] Russia (Udmurtia)
Date: Thu 19 Dec 2013
Source: Izvestia [in Russian, trans., edited]
http://www.izvestiaur.ru/news/view/8222701.html


An unfavourable epidemiological situation with regard to measles virus infection exists in Udmurtia at the present time. The Rospotrebnadzor [Federal Service for Consumer Protection and Human Welfare] press service has reported that during 2013 a total of 12 people, including 3 children, have been hospitalised. 8 of these patients, including 3 children under 2 years of age, are confirmed cases of measles by laboratory diagnosis. 9 of the adults and 3 of the children had not received measles vaccination. 11 of these patients were from Izhevsk and one from Glazov. All are workers in at risk occupations -- workers in trade and public catering, individual entrepreneurs.

An investigation has found that the initial cases were associated with a trip to Moscow to the "Lublin" market, where cases of measles were reported in October and November [2013].

In 2012, 39 cases of measles, 12 of them children. In most cases, the sick had not been vaccinated against measles and the outbreak spread by nosocomial infection among unvaccinated people. It is believed that the measles virus had been imported from Thailand. Prior to that, by 2005 Udmurtia had been declared free of measles virus infection.

According to experts, the only effective way to protect against measles is vaccination. Vaccination is routinely administered twice to children at 1 year and 6 years of age. Adults are not vaccinated provided they have documentation of previous vaccination or have been vaccinated twice with an interval of 6 months. Once administered, measles vaccination protects for life.

In Udmurtia about 2000 children have been fully vaccinated by the age of 6, and another 1445 have received at least one dose (72.2 per cent). The main reason for the of persistence of measles is the relatively large number of unvaccinated children -- 1252 or 63 per cent.

